Now a bost{er} on benche bibbes þerof
Tyl he be dronkken as þe deuel, & dotes þ{er} he syttes;
So þe worcher of þis worlde wlates þer-wyth,
Þat i{n} þe poynt of her play he poruayes a mynde;
He wayned hem a warny{n}g þat wonder hem þoȝt.
Nov is alle þis guere geten glotou{n}es to serue;

Tune--"_Had I the wyte she bade me._"
Had I the wyte, had I the wyte,
Had I the wyte she bade me;
She watch'd me by the hie-gate side.
And up the loan she shaw'd me;
And when I wadna venture in,
A coward loon she ca'd me;
Had kirk and state been in the gate,

And when your back begins to smart,
It's like a penknife in your heart;
And when your heart begins to bleed,
You're dead, and dead, and dead indeed.
As wet as a fish--as dry as a bone;
As live as a bird--as dead as a stone;
As plump as a partridge--as poor as a rat;
As strong as a horse--as weak as a cat;
As hard as a flint--as soft as a mole;
As white as a lily--as black as a coal;

& I schal wy{n}ne yow wyȝt of wat{er} a lyttel,
& fast aboute schal I fare yo{ur} fette wer waschene;
